<% content_for :title, "PostgreSQL Embeddings Service" %>
<% content_for :subtitle do %>
    A subclassable vector similarity search service for semantic text matching
<% end %>

<%= h2_with_anchor "Overview" %>

<p>Langgraph Feature (not Rails): </p>

<p>The <code>PostgresEmbeddingsService</code> provides a generic, reusable foundation for building semantic search capabilities using PostgreSQL's pgvector extension. This service powers various AI-driven features across the application by enabling similarity-based text retrieval.</p>

<div class="alert alert-info">
    <p><strong>Key Use Cases:</strong></p>
    <ul>
        <li>Semantic search across documents and code</li>
        <li>Finding similar content based on meaning, not just keywords</li>
        <li>Building specialized search tools (icons, files, documentation)</li>
        <li>Intelligent caching of embedding results</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<%= h2_with_anchor "Architecture" %>

<p>The service leverages several key technologies:</p>

<ol>
    <li><strong>PostgreSQL with pgvector</strong>: Stores and searches vector embeddings</li>
    <li><strong>OpenAI Embeddings</strong>: Converts text to high-dimensional vectors</li>
    <li><strong>LangChain PGVector</strong>: Manages vector store operations</li>
    <li><strong>Built-in Caching</strong>: Reduces API calls and improves performance</li>
</ol>

<%= h3_with_anchor "How It Works" %>

<pre><code class="language-mermaid">
graph LR
    A[Text Input] --> B[Generate Embedding]
    B --> C{Check Cache}
    C -->|Cache Hit| D[Return Cached Results]
    C -->|Cache Miss| E[Vector Similarity Search]
    E --> F[PostgreSQL pgvector]
    F --> G[Rank by Similarity]
    G --> H[Cache Results]
    H --> I[Return Results]
</code></pre>

<%= h2_with_anchor "Core Features" %>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Vector Storage" %>

<p>Store text with its vector representation for future similarity searches:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">await embeddingsService.storeEmbeddings([
    {
        pageContent: "User authentication flow",
        metadata: { 
            docId: "auth-001",
            category: "authentication" 
        }
    },
    {
        pageContent: "Payment processing system",
        metadata: { 
            docId: "payment-002",
            category: "billing" 
        }
    }
]);</code></pre>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Similarity Search" %>

<p>Find semantically similar content based on meaning:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// Single query search
const results = await embeddingsService.search(
    "login and security",  // Query
    5,                      // Top K results
    {
        filter: { category: "authentication" },  // Optional metadata filter
        includeEmbedding: false                   // Don't return raw vectors
    }
);

// Results include similarity scores
results.forEach(doc => {
    console.log(`Score: ${doc.similarityScore}, Content: ${doc.pageContent}`);
});</code></pre>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Multi-Query Search" %>

<p>Execute multiple searches in parallel for better performance:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">const results = await embeddingsService.multiQuerySearch(
    ["user profile", "settings page", "dashboard"],  // Multiple queries
    3  // Top K per query
);

// Returns array of result sets, one per query</code></pre>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Hybrid Search" %>

<p>Combine semantic vector search with traditional text matching:</p>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">// The service automatically enhances vector search with ILIKE matching
// This catches exact matches that might have lower semantic similarity
const results = await embeddingsService.search(
    "PostgresEmbeddingsService",  // Exact class name
    5
);
// Will find both semantic matches AND exact text matches</code></pre>

<%= h2_with_anchor "Caching System" %>

<p>The service includes an intelligent caching layer that significantly improves performance:</p>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Cache Configuration" %>

<pre><code class="language-typescript">const service = new PostgresEmbeddingsService({
    tableName: "my_embeddings",
    cacheOptions: {
        ttlHours: 24,           // Cache lifetime (default: 24 hours)
        minSimilarity: 0.25     // Minimum score to cache (default: 0.25)
    }
});</code></pre>

<%= h3_with_anchor "How Caching Works" %>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Query Hashing</strong>: Each search query is hashed with its parameters</li>
    <li><strong>TTL Management</strong>: Cached results expire after the configured time</li>
    <li><strong>Similarity Threshold</strong>: Only results above the threshold are cached</li>
    <li><strong>Automatic Cleanup</strong>: Expired cache entries are removed on access</li>
</ol>

<%= h2_with_anchor "Database Schema" %>

<p>Use Rails to provide your subclass with a matching database schema.</p>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Embeddings Table" %>

<pre><code class="language-ruby">
    create_table :icon_embeddings do |t|
      t.string :key, null: false
      t.text :text, null: false
      t.vector :embedding, limit: 1536, null: false
      t.jsonb :metadata, null: false, default: {}
      t.timestamp :created_at

      t.index :key, unique: true
    end

    safety_assured do
      execute "CREATE INDEX idx_icon_embeddings_text ON icon_embeddings USING IVFFlat (embedding vector_cosine_ops);"
    end
</code></pre>

<%= h3_with_anchor "Cache Table" %>

Optionally, you can create a cache table which will be used to store the results of previous searches. 

This can be useful for reducing the number of API calls to the embedding model and improving performance.

<pre><code class="language-ruby">
    create_table :icon_query_caches do |t|
      t.string :query, null: false
      t.jsonb :results, null: false, default: []
      t.integer :use_count, null: false, default: 0
      t.integer :ttl_seconds, null: false, default: 86400
      t.float :min_similarity, null: false, default: 0.7
      t.integer :top_k, null: false
      t.timestamp :last_used_at, null: false
      t.timestamps

      t.index :query
      t.index :top_k
      t.index :use_count
      t.index :ttl_seconds
      t.index :last_used_at
      t.index :min_similarity
    end
</code></pre>

